[[File:Green envelope.jpg|thumb|Green envelopes for sale at the [[Surabaya]] market]]
[[File:Amplop hijau.jpg|thumb|Green envelopes in Indonesia (2016)]]
A '''green envelope''' (Malay: '''''sampul hijau''''' or '''''sampul duit raya''''') is a [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]] adaptation of the Chinese [[red envelope]] custom. During the festival of [[Eid ul-Fitr]], [[Islam in Malaysia|Muslims in Malaysia]], [[Islam in Brunei|Brunei]], [[Islam in Singapore|Singapore]], and [[Islam in Indonesia|Indonesia]] hand out money in green [[envelope]]s to guests who visit their homes.<ref>http://design-cu.jp/iasdr2013/papers/1893-1b.pdf</ref> The colour [[Green#Green_in_Islam|green]] was chosen for its association with the [[Islamic paradise]]. The idea of handing out green envelopes is based on the Islamic concept of ''[[zakat]]'', where every Muslim is required to provide at least 2.5% of their wealth to the needy. However, Malays now hand out these green envelopes during ''Aidilfitri'' not only to their poor guests, but also to the [[middle class]] and to the [[upper class]]. The amount of money depends on how much the host can afford to give their guests.

